<br>
He gathered the heavy brown cloak about him and fastened the clasp about the neck; a brass fixing in the shape of five pointed crescents in a circle.  Beneath the cloak he wore a black robe, its folds ragged and torn where the heavy fabric had been worn in battle.  The guise was awkward and crude, but he was no fool.  A fully armed Iksar, striding into a tavern full of softlings?  Bah.  More effort than it was worth.  He flattened his tail against his back and tested his legs. It would be hard to balance, but he could manage.  He drew the long, dark hood over his face and snout, and made his way to the ground.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oyi! Oyi!  You theah!  Ain't ya got anythin' fer a poor, out'a'work Gnome?&quot;  The beggar moaned pitifully at Kelisk, his palms outstretched to recieve whatever coin he could get.  Kelisk drew the hood back and hissed angrily at the creature, whose face twisted into an unsure terror before the Spirit horns flashed from beneath the arms of the robe, and the gnome's hands dropped to the ground.  <br>
Confused, the Gnome could utter no sound as he shook in horror, his arms still stretched before him, ending in clean, bloodied nubs.  Kelisk took one of the hands from the ground and smiled to himself.  The Brood of Kotiz would have much pleasure studying this.  He shoved it into his satchel and calmly struck the Gnome across the head with a powerful kick, rendering it unconscious as it twitched silently on the reddened stones.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ksah... how I hate delays.&quot;<br>
<br>
